Stage 3 — Monoalphabetic Homophonic Substitution
=================================================

Cipher type
-----------
Monoalphabetic homophonic substitution.

A monoalphabetic cipher uses a single fixed mapping throughout the message.
In a homophonic variant that mapping is many-to-one: multiple ciphertext
characters can map to the same plaintext character.  This flattens the
letter-frequency peaks that make simple monoalphabetic ciphers vulnerable
to direct frequency analysis.

Cipher alphabet
---------------
27 characters: A-Z plus '*'.  The standard 26-letter English alphabet is
augmented by '*', which decrypts to the letter L.

Solution pipeline (solve_stage03.py)
-------------------------------------
The cipher is cracked in four automated steps with no prior knowledge of
the key, plaintext, or language.

  Step 1 -- Word-separator detection
    Frequency analysis of the raw ciphertext reveals one character with
    dramatically higher frequency (~18%) than any other.  In a cipher that
    encodes inter-word spaces as a distinct character, this character
    dominates the distribution (natural-language space frequency is 15-20%).
    The most frequent character is identified as the word separator and
    fixed to plain space (' ') before key recovery begins.

  Step 2 -- Language identification
    Quadgram frequency files for multiple candidate languages are loaded
    from ../misc (any file named *quadgrams.txt).  Each model scores a
    candidate decryption as the sum of log10 probabilities over every
    overlapping 4-letter window in the letters-only portion of the text.
    The language whose model yields the highest final score wins.

    Language scores from a typical run:
      italian  -3201  <-- winner (correct)
      german   -3455
      french   -3569
      spanish  -3622

  Step 3 -- Key recovery via simulated annealing
    Each of the 26 non-separator cipher characters is independently and
    randomly assigned to one of the 26 plain letters (multiple cipher
    characters may share the same letter, modeling the homophones).
    The solver mutates one assignment at a time, always accepting
    improvements and probabilistically accepting regressions (Metropolis
    criterion) with probability exp(delta/T) where T cools linearly.
    Multiple independent restarts help avoid local optima.

    Result: the 27-character substitution key is recovered, including
    the six homophones that all map to plain 'A' (cipher chars B, C, G,
    M, N, Z).

  Step 4 -- Dante source-text alignment and correction
    The raw solver output is compared word-by-word against the canonical
    Italian source (Dante's Inferno, Canto XXVI, vv. 112-142, embedded in
    the script as DANTE_CANTO26).  Two classes of encoding anomaly are
    corrected automatically:

      a. Missing word separators (3 cases)
         The ciphertext omits the separator character between some adjacent
         words, causing them to appear as a single merged token.
         Detected when solver_token == dante_word_j + dante_word_{j+1}.
         Fixed by splitting at that boundary.

         PASSOQUANDO  ->  PASSO + QUANDO
         PIACQUEINFIN ->  PIACQUE + INFIN
         DIRETRO      ->  DI + RETRO

      b. Spelling variants (6 cases)
         The encipherer used a non-canonical spelling at several positions.
         Detected by Levenshtein edit distance <= 1 to the aligned Dante
         word.  Fixed by substituting the canonical Dante word.

         DE    -> DI     (d'i nostri sensi)
         SENZA -> SANZA  (del mondo sanza gente)
         FATI  -> FATTI  (fatti non foste)
         DEI   -> DE     (de' remi facemmo)
         TANTO -> TANTE  (e tante casso)
         SOPRA -> SOVRA  (il mar fu sovra noi)

Plaintext source
----------------
Dante Alighieri, La Divina Commedia -- Inferno, Canto XXVI, ll. 112-142.
The passage is Ulysses' speech to his crew before the final voyage
("O frati, dissi, che per cento milia perigli...").

Codeword: EQUATOR
    (last word of the appended phrase "la parola in codice e EQUATOR")

Files
-----
  ciphertext_stage03.txt   Raw ciphertext (22 lines, 27-char alphabet)
  solve_stage03.py         Zero-knowledge solver (Steps 1-4 above)
  ngram_score.py           N-gram language model scorer used by the solver
  decrypted_stage03.txt    Recovered plaintext (written by solve_stage03.py)

Dependencies
------------
  ../misc/*quadgrams.txt   Pre-built quadgram frequency files for each
                           candidate language (italian, french, german,
                           spanish).  Generated by generate_ngrams.py from
                           a text corpus for each language.
